Public ownership of needs is one possible option for mitigating climate change, but it is not a complete answer in and of itself. Climate change is a difficult subject that must be addressed in a diverse manner. Public ownership of essentials such as electricity, transportation, and housing may aid in the promotion of sustainable development and the reduction of greenhouse gas emissions. For example, public ownership of energy utilities may aid in the promotion of renewable energy, while public ownership of transportation can aid in the promotion of public transit and electric automobiles. Similarly, public housing ownership may encourage energy efficiency and sustainable construction techniques. Furthermore, public ownership of essentials may foster fairness and social justice. By making these essentials available as a public service, it is possible to assure that they are available to all members of society, regardless of economic level or social rank. It is crucial to stress, however, that public ownership of basics is not the sole answer to climate change. Other solutions, such as carbon price, legislation, and R&D spending, are also vital in solving this problem. Furthermore, the possible negatives of public ownership must be considered, such as the necessity for good control and regulation, the possibility of political influence, and the requirement for enough finance. To summarize, public ownership of needs is one possible option for mitigating climate change, but it is not a complete answer on its own. It is critical to assess the possible advantages and downsides of this method, as well as acknowledge that it must be part of a multidimensional approach to climate change mitigation. 